reference mission_constants as c

submodel rover as rover_a
submodel rover as rover_b

section Masses

    ~~~
    The spacecraft dry mass is the total mass after the main propulsion burn,
    consisting of the bus structure plus all rovers.

    Wet mass (before burn) equals dry mass plus propellant:

    $$m_{wet} = m_{dry} + m_{req}$$
    ~~~

Vehicle dry mass: m_bus = 4000 :kg

    ~ Bus structure, avionics, and propulsion hardware. Does not include propellant or rover payload.

Rover payload mass: m_pl = m.rover_a + m.rover_b :kg

    ~~~
    Sum of both rover masses. Since each rover is a submodel,
    changes to one rover do not affect the other.
    ~~~

$ Dry mass after maneuver: m_dry = m_bus + m_pl :kg

    ~~~
    The mass the vehicle must carry after expending all propellant.
    This is the denominator of the mass ratio in the rocket equation:

    $$\mu = \frac{m_{wet}}{m_{dry}} = e^{\Delta v / v_e}$$

    A higher mass ratio demands exponentially more propellant.
    ~~~

section Propulsion

    ~~~
    Propulsion sizing follows the Tsiolkovsky rocket equation [@Tsiolkovsky1903].
    The effective exhaust velocity $v_e$ relates to specific impulse $I_{sp}$ by:

    $$v_e = I_{sp} \cdot g_0$$

    where $g_0 = 9.81\,m/s^2$ is standard gravity.
    For a bipropellant MMH/NTO engine, $I_{sp} \approx 300\,s$,
    giving $v_e \approx 2943\,m/s$ [@Sutton2017].
    ~~~

Effective exhaust velocity: v_e = 9.81*300 :m/s

    ~~~
    Specific impulse times standard gravity. Corresponds to
    $I_{sp} \approx 300\,s$, typical for pressure-fed MMH/NTO
    bipropellant engines.
    ~~~

Loaded propellant available: m_p0 = 15000 :kg

    ~ Propellant capacity of the main tank.

Tsiolkovsky propellant required: m_req = m_dry * (e ^ (dv.c / v_e) - 1) :kg

    ~~~
    Derived directly from the rocket equation. Starting from:

    $$\Delta v = v_e \ln\!\frac{m_{wet}}{m_{dry}}$$

    Substituting $m_{wet} = m_{dry} + m_{req}$ and solving for $m_{req}$:

    $$m_{req} = m_{dry}\!\left(e^{\Delta v / v_e} - 1\right) \implies {{m_req:equation}}$$

    The exponential dependence on $\Delta v / v_e$ makes this the primary
    mission driver.
    ~~~

$ Wet mass at ignition: m_wet = m_dry + m_req :kg

    ~ Total spacecraft mass at start of burn.

$ Propellant margin(-1e30, 1e30): m_mg = m_p0 - m_req :kg

    ~ Positive margin means the mission is feasible. Negative means it cannot close.

section Derived Quantities

$ Mass ratio: mu = m_wet / m_dry

    ~~~
    The Tsiolkovsky mass ratio. Typical values: $\mu \approx 2$ for Earth-orbit
    missions, $\mu \approx 3$--$5$ for interplanetary missions.
    ~~~

test: m_req < m_p0
